I'm a nurse who is also a PhD student, which is shocking to me everyday single day considering I didn't think I would even go to a 4-year college (I was not a top student by any means). 

I was first attracted to nursing, because I wanted to work 3 days a week and play the other 4. Many personal and professional experiences have affected me since I decided to apply for nursing school, but after my time in the neonatal intensive care unit I realized that finding out "why" was what would really feed my soul. Why are some kids born battling such difficult social, economic, and health circumstances and how can we level the playing field for them. 

In my research I ask what are the social, economic, and individual factors that affect the health of pregnant women and their babies and how can we intervene to improve their health?

Stephanie is Executive & Creative Director of The People?s Science, a non-profit organization committed to engaging STEM learners and cultivating an informed citizenry. Previously, she developed educational technology and public exhibits for Oregon Health & Science University, where she was also trained in developmental neuroscience research. She continued her post-bac training in psychology and neuroscience at Harvard University from 2012-2016, through which she has co-authored over a dozen academic presentations.

She has taught and developed multimedia curriculum for Harvard Graduate School of Education, Harvard Faculty of Arts & Sciences, Emerson College, and Portland State University. In 2015, she received a Spark Grant Award from Harvard Initiative for Learning and Teaching for her work developing scientific literacy skills in undergraduate students.

Stephanie has an Ed.M. in Mind, Brain, and Education studies from the Harvard Graduate School of Education (HGSE), where she was selected as the 2013 Leadership in Education Award recipient. Alongside her work in education and technology, Stephanie is a contributing writer at the Learning & The Brain blog.

a:2:{s:2:"id";i:929;s:7:"content";s:861:"The human brain is truly an astounding bit of biology! With it we have harnessed the power of Nature and constructed entire civilizations. Our capacity for problem solving and innovation has its roots in the way that we can consider problems as detached from our immediate sensory environment: we extrapolate and we think in terms of concepts.

The human imagination is limitless. As an example ? you could close your eyes right now and imagine any scene ? riding a horse through a field, or seeing a waterfall on a sunny day ? and, as if from the void, this scene presents itself to your mind?s eye for you to behold.

How is this possible? What is it about the brain that lets us perform these mental reconstructions? And how important is this process to our survival and evolution?

These are some of the questions that keep me wide-eyed and curious.";}
Lauren Jabusch Biological Systems Engineering, Renewable Energy, Integrated Agriculture, Wastewater Treatment
